entry.title: [iOS][sync] Avoid IsSyncRequested() in ManageSyncSettingsMediator
entry.content:
The usage of IsSyncRequested() to gray out the toggles appears to be

legacy, from the time when the UI allowed disabling the sync-requested

bit.



Starting with https://crrev.com/3625480, IsSyncRequested() is always

true, except for one edge case, which is the only behavioral change in

this patch: if the user signs out, there is some short time during

which the UI continues to be displayed. Before this patch, the toggles

turned gray during this time, whereas after this patch nothing changes

in the UI (which is arguably a better UX). In the hypothetical case

where the user managed to interact with the toggles in this short time

interval, nothing really bad happens (it's similar to interacting with

the toggles *before* signing out).



This removes the last remaining calling site to the deprecated

SyncSetupService::IsSyncRequested().

entry.title: Ensure on-page javascript runs for single-page apps
entry.content:
This patch ensures that the on-page meta extraction for product info

in the shopping service runs for different navigations in single-page

web apps. The 'DidFinishedLoading' signal is still used, but is

supplemented by 'DidStopLoading' which is observed after a navigation

has finished. The script is run 2 seconds after the last "stopped

loading" event and is still only run once per unique page. Coverage

will be higher as a result of this work.



The added delay in running javascript also impacts how a number of

metrics are recorded in the shopping service. Specifically, if a

user navigates prior to getting a result from the javascript, the

metric will not be recorded. This impacts the following:



- Commerce.ShoppingService.ProductInfo.FallbackDataContent

- Commerce.ShoppingService.ProductInfo.FallbackDataUsed

- Commerce.ShoppingService.ProductInfo.ImageAvailability



Bug: b:278870444

entry.title: [SuperSize] Add ARSC Count Metrics.
entry.content:
This CL adds ARSC metrics data (counts of types for each ARSC file) to

.size files, updates the Viewer to show them, and changes Metrics Tree

subcategories from "SIZE metrics" / "COUNT metrics" to "Size" / "Count".



In the Metrics View, items were previously classified as "ELF" or "DEX"

by checking whether or not the metric suffix (e.g., "SIZE/.text" =>

".text") has "." (e.g., ".text" has "." => "ELF"). However, we're now

adding "ARSC" to the mix, making the old scheme is obsolete.



The new classification scheme is to examine, for each metric item, the

extensions of associated files (files shown as table rows). For Chrome,

we consistently have ".so" => "ELF", ".dex"=> "DEX", ".arsc" => "ARSC",

allowing easy classification. To handle edge cases, we also assign empty

extension => "ELF" and mixed / unknown extension => "OTHER".



Details:

* apk.py: CreateArscSymbols(): For each RES_TABLE_TYPE_TYPE chunk,

create count metrics entry, e.g., "COUNT/anim" -> 100.

* archive.py: _CreateContainerSymbols(): Add the above.

* ui-base.js: Add helper getFileExtension().

* state.js: Add metrics icon "arsc" and "other", reusing existing ones.

* metrics-tree-ui.js: MetricsTreeModel:

* makeMetricNode(): Implement the new metric item classification

scheme via file extensions.

* extractAndStoreRoot(): Change subcategory names; create Sets of

associated extensions for each metric item for classification.

entry.title: [Metadata][VCN][Settings Page][Android] Fix Capital One icon size
entry.content:
The Capital One icon for virtual cards is of larger size than other

credit card icons.



Screenshot (issue): https://screenshot.googleplex.com/5tEppnMRXF82LMQ



We have experiments in which we show icons of different sizes on

different surfaces. We also cache icons in required sizes against their

URLs for faster retrieval. All card arts except the Capital One icon for

virtual cards are available in any required size, and can be fetched by

appending the specs to the URL. Since this icon is available via a

static URL, it gets cached in a single size (size of the first surfaced

icon). This causes some surfaces to show this icon in incorrect size.



Enable caching this icon at different sizes by appending size specs

while caching.

entry.title: Re-write ArchivableCredentialStore/ASCredentialIdentityStore on startup
entry.content:
ArchivableCredentialStore & ASCredentialIdentityStore are the de facto

stores powering "Passwords in other apps". Let's call them "CPE stores"

to distinguish from PasswordStore, Chrome's source of truth.



Before this CL, the write frequency to the CPE stores was this:

1. Once, read the whole content of PasswordStore and overwrite.

This codepath was more relevant when CPE first launched and it was

executed for existing Chrome installs, where PasswordStore was non

empty. Now it only runs for new installs, reading nothing and

writing nothing.

2. Handle changes in PasswordStoreInterface::Observer::OnLoginsChanged()

This is the most relevant codepath. However, I *think* adding the

observer might race with Sync downloading new passwords.

An interesting note is that even though the implementation pretends to

do incremental writes, in the end every password is re-written, c.f.

[ArchivableCredentialStore saveDataWithCompletion:].

3. When the primary gaia ID changes, read everything and overwrite.

This is mostly a technical detail. The entries in the CPE stores

contain the gaia ID as a field, so this is necessary.



Why change it:

- Concern for the consistency between PasswordStore and the CPE stores.

Not every observer notification might arrive in 2). In fact the docs

of OnLoginsChanged() discourage relying on removal notifications.

- By the time this CL rolls out, the new "account" PasswordStore

will be already populated for some users. Even if we inject the

new object in CredentialProviderService, none of 1, 2, 3 guarantees

those passwords to be written to the CPE stores (though in practice

2 will eventually trigger).



Change it to what:

- Only change 1. Instead of this being a one-off write, do it on

every startup. Post a delayed task for performance reasons.

entry.title: iOS sync settings: Ensure IsSetupInProgress is true while settings open
entry.content:
While any Sync-settings UI is open, it should hold a SyncSetupInProgress

handle, to ensure that SyncService::IsSetupInProgress() is true as long

as the UI is open. (This ensures that any pending changes don't get

applied until the user confirms/closes the UI.)



Previously, the iOS sync settings UI did this, but a bit inconsistently

(basically it grabbed a SyncSetupInProgressHandle on the first change,

but (a) it's not clear if that actually covered all changes, and (b)

with some upcoming changes that's not good enough, since

IsSetupInProgress() needs to be true as soon as the UI is opened).



After this CL, the settings coordinator explicitly marks setup as in

progress before showing the UI. The previous ad-hoc logic in

SyncSetupService is replaced by CHECKs.

This makes the IsSetupIsProgress() state more reliable, and consistent

with how it works on all other platforms.

entry.title: [FilesBulkPinning] Expose kOkWithMoreResults drivefs result
entry.content:
When searching for items, it's possible to hit the end of the locally

available results but have some cloud results that are still potentially

available. This is only really required when the QuerySource is

`kLocalAndCloud` as it tries a local search first then defers to the

cloud.



Currently the logic is an empty page indicates the end of a query.

However when using `kLocalAndCloud` this logic is incorrect. To avoid

terminating the query at empty pages, provide another `FileError` called

`kOkWithMoreResults` to indicate the local results have been exhausted

and to try `GetNextPage` again to search the cloud. If the subsequent

search returns `kOk` with an empty page, this is the final result.

entry.title: Fix HasIsolatedStorage() for non-enabled extensions
entry.content:
HasIsolatedStorage() incorrectly returns false for extensions with

isolated storage that are not enabled, because it only checks the

enabled list.



This use case is relevant when an extension with isolated storage is

disabled. In this process, the extension is moved to the disabled list

of the ExtensionRegistry and then, among other actions, the extension

service worker is told to unregister. In order to obtain the service

worker context, HasIsolatedStorage() is used to determine the

StoragePartitionConfig of the extension. Because at this point the

extension is already moved to the disabled list, HasIsolatedStorage()

returns false, even though the extension has isolated storage and thus the incorrect ServiceWorkerContext is obtained (not the one in which

the extension actually has a service worker running). This leads to

the extensions's service worker not actually unregistering and still

running.



This issue is fixed by HasIsolatedStorage() checking the extensions in

both the enabled and disabled extension lists.



Bug: b:279763783

entry.title: Add browser tests for extension printer printable area
entry.content:
There are no browser tests that cover extension printer handling code.

Modify the test printer extension to implement the

chrome.printerProvider API and provide dummy extension printers. In

tests, add the extension printer ids to sticky settings, which will

cause Print Preview to request extension printers. This will trigger

extension printer handling code.



This setup would have allowed us to catch crbug.com/1432309 if an

extension printer with missing printable area was provided.
